defaultChanges to the dual candidacy ban
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Government of Wales Act, 2006 introduced a prohibition on “dual candidacy”, that is candidates standing for election in the constituencies and on the regional list simultaneously. This is an anomaly and out of line with virtually all other Additional M
defaultember Systems (AMS). Furthermore, it has a serious impact on capacity with regard to quality of candidates that parties might put up (and, therefore, of elected AMs). The Wales Office Green Paper (2012) 
defaulton future electoral arrangements for the National Ass
defaultembly for Wales
default default(
defaulthttp://www.walesoffice.gov.uk/have-your-say-2/
default) suggested removing the ban
default saying that the
default UK Government believes: 
default&#xa0;
default“that, in principle, candidates should not be barred from standing for election simultaneously in an Assembly constituency and an Assembly region. It impacts disproportionally on smaller parties, who would understandably not wish to risk their smaller pool
default of candidates in a constituency election when there may be a chance they could be elected from the regional list. Likewise, if a party does better than expected in constituency elections, candidates on that party’s regional list are unlikely to be elected
default. The prohibition on dual candidacy may, in time, have a negative effect on representation in the Assembly as high quality candidates who stand as constituency candidates, but who fail to secure that seat, are lost to the Assembly because of the “all or no
defaultthing” choice they are required to make.” 
default&#xa0;
defaultI agree
default entirely
default with the removal of the restriction in the draft Bill
default.
default The ban introduced in 2006 was ill-advised and has affected 
defaultboth 
defaultcapacity and calibre
default,
default especially given the 
defaultsplit 
defaultbetween list and constitue
defaultncy seats in the Welsh system. 
defaultIn other nations that use similar Additional Mixed 
defaultMember 
defaultSystems (AMS), there is no such restriction. Indeed, a 
defaultrecent Electoral Commission 
defaultreport 
defaultin New Zealand rejected a ban
default,
default as did the Arbuthnot
defaultt
default Commission in Scotland. 
defaultIssues about mandate and procedures 
defaultbetween constituency and regional members 
defaulthave been successfully resolved elsewhere
default,
default and there is 
defaultno reason to think W
defaultales is different in this regard.
