defaultIncreasing the number of AMs 
default&#xa0;defaultIt is hard to disprove that substan
defaulttial capacity constraints arise from having such a relatively small number of AMs. Any longitudinal
default review of devolution in
default Wales 
defaultand strategic planning for the future of the Assembly 
defaultmeans that at some stage the
default core
default capacity issues will 
defaulthave to be addressed, otherwise there 
defaultwill be an inevitable
default continued impact on the profile, effectiveness and legitimacy of the Assembly
default. 
defaultIt is, however, critical to consider the number of politicians representing Wales and its localities in the round, th
defaultat is at European, UK, national and local level.
default Equally, it lends weight to Section 3 of Part One of the Bill which rightly prohibits the holding of a seat in both the UK Parliament and the Assembly.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultResearch undertaken by McAllister (
defaultin 
default2008-9
default, whilst 
defaultworking with the Independent Panel on AMs Pay and Support
default) and Cole et al (2013) 
defaulthas 
defaultexamined alternatives to 
defaultincreasing the finite number of AMs. It should be noted that each of these is far from perfect as they are essentially temporary solutions to symp
defaulttoms of a core problem.
