default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultShorter-term alternatives: 
defaultAssembly
default A
defaultssociates
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is 
defaultsome 
defaultmerit in considering the appointment of a small number of individuals to serve on Assembly committees with the paramount objective of enhancing opportunities for 
defaultscrutiny.  Such a proposal would build on practice
default already underway
default in local authorities, where scrutiny committees often appoint independent members 
defaultas a means of 
defaultenhanc
defaulting
default capacity (Wilson and Game
default, 2011). The suggestion for Assembly Associates was raise
defaultd by McAllister in research papers provided for the Independent Panel on AMs Pay and Support (2008-9) and in recent work on Assembly capacity with Cole et al (2013). 
default&#xa0;
defaultSuch Associates 
defaultmight each serve for no more than four years and would have an unpaid an
defaultd non-voting status. 
defaultAs well as 
defaultaugment
defaulting
default in
defaultternal
default expertise
default for effective scrutiny
default, this
default would have the added bonus of presenting greater 
defaultdiversity and experience to the 
defaultwork of the 
defaultAssembly.  
defaultOf course, there are 
defaultdifficulties with this suggestion
default especially 
defaultwith regard to 
defaultdemocratic legitimacy: Cole et al (2013)
default suggest that it would not be appropriate to appoint more
default than
default six 
defaultat any one time to ensure that 
defaultelected AMs 
defaultwould 
defaultretain at least a 10-1 ratio.
default Although this is an interesting
default 
defaultinnovation,
default clearly it is an experimental one and one moreover, that is wholly unfamiliar to a UK parliamentary context. In addition, 
defaultthe 
defaultlikely financial 
defaultdifferential between
default 
defaultpursuing
default one of these routes 
defaultor
default having more directly AMs is minimal
default.
default&#xa0;
default
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default‘Overhang’ seats
default&#xa0;
defaultA m
defaultechanism for providing additional AMs without formally increasing the size of the Assembly 
defaultcould
default lie in the concept of ‘
defaulto
defaultverhang seats’ (used in the New Zealand Parliament, the German Bundestag and the National Assembly of Venezuela). The need for ‘overhan
defaultg seats’ arises when a party in a Mixed Member Electoral System wins 
defaultmore constituency seats than its share of seats determined by the party vote (that is, its overall proportional entitlement). In such cases, the extra seats are not normally removed, rath
defaulter the number of representatives in parliament increases just for the life of that parliament, so adding to its capacity (Soberg Shugart and Wattenberg, 2003; National Assembly Independent Review Panel, 2009). 
